(117, 1, '2012-06-29 04:34:20', '2012-06-29 04:34:20', '<h2>Director</h2>\r\n<strong>Dr. Larry Hajime Shinagawa</strong>\r\nDirector, Asian American Studies Program\r\nAssociate Professor, University of Maryland\r\nDepartment of American Studies\r\nEmail: <a href="mailto:lshinaga@umd.edu">lshinaga@umd.edu</a>\r\n\r\nDr. Shinagawa''s research areas include the social demography of racial groups in the United States, intermarriage, multiracial identity, and Asian American culture and community. Before coming to the University of Maryland, he was the Director of the Center for the Study of Culture, Race, and Ethnicity and was an associate professor of the Sociology Department of Ithaca College.\r\n\r\nDr. Shinagawa has been an author/co-author and editor/co-editor of notable articles, books, anthologies and book series related to ethnic studies, multicultural education, Asian Americans and demography. He is currently on the Board of Directors of the National Association for Ethnic Studies. He also participates as a board member for other national and regional non-profit, community-based organizations and research organizations. Dr. Shinagawa received his Ph.D. in Sociology from the University of California, Berkeley, as well as a B.A. in Sociology and a B.A. in Ethnic Studies.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2>Core Faculty</h2>\r\n<img src="http://localhost/%7Erajankz/aast/media/images/people/lisa_mar.jpg" alt="" width="97px" height="113px" /><strong>Dr. Lisa R. Mar</strong>\r\nAssociate Professor, Department of History\r\nUniversity of Maryland\r\nEmail: <a href="mailto:lmar@umd.edu">lmar@umd.edu</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nDr. Mar teaches about past and present Asian Americans, as well as immigrants, in the United States. Her research interests are in immigration, politics, law, and culture. She often employs a transnational perspective that brings together the United States, China, and Canada. In 2010, Oxford University Press published Dr. Mar''s book, Brokering Belonging: Chinese in the Exclusion Era, 1885-1945. Dr. Mar is currently working on two more book projects related to Chinese immigrants: a study of Second World War experiences, and a history of Chinese American religious life.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nDr. Mar has published articles relating to transnational Chinese migration history, domestic violence in immigrant contexts, comparative U.S.-Canadian history, and immigrant family life. She also served as a researcher and advisor for the PBS Asian American history series, Ancestors in the Americas. Professor Mar has held a number of prestigious fellowships. Among them, the Andrew W. Mellon Fellowship in Humanistic Studies and The Queen''s Fellowship of the Social Sciences and Humanities Research Council of Canada (SSHRC). Dr. Mar also received a CTE Grant to develop a new course on Asian Americans in Washington, D.C. Dr. Mar graduated with a B.A. in History from Stanford University. She received her Ph.D. and M.A. in History from the University of Toronto.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<img src="http://localhost/%7Erajankz/aast/media/images/people/julie_park.jpg" alt="" width="97px" height="113px" /><strong>Dr. Julie Park</strong>\r\nAssociate Professor, Department of Sociology\r\nUniversity of Maryland\r\nEmail: <a href="mailto:juliepar@umd.edu">juliepar@umd.edu</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nDr. Park teaches Introduction to Asian Americans Studies. Prior to joining the Maryland faculty in 2008, she was a research assistant professor in the School of Policy, Planning, and Development and the associate director of the Population Dynamics Research Group at the University of Southern California. She received her Ph.D. (2003) and M.A. (2001) in Sociology as well as a Master''s in Urban Planning (1998) from the University of Southern California. She received her B.A. in Sociology at the University of California, Davis.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nProfessor Park''s research focuses on the adaptation process of immigrants in the United States, which includes the areas of immigration, demography, race, and urban studies. Her dissertation work focused on the socioeconomic adaptation of Southeast Asian immigrants. More broadly, she examines how various immigrant groups improve their socioeconomic status. In addition, she has constructed an innovative cohort method to assess the intergenerational mobility across immigrant generations. Lastly, Professor Park considers how residential segregation changes in new and established immigrant gateways.\r\n<a name="affiliate-faculty"></a>\r\n<h2>Affiliate Faculty</h2>\r\n<strong>Dr. Jason C. Kuo</strong>(<a href="mailto:jck@umd.edu">jck@umd.edu</a>)\r\nProfessor\r\nDepartment of Art History and Archaeology\r\nUniversity of Maryland\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Dr. Timothy Ng</strong>(<a href="mailto:binkley@umd.edu">binkley@umd.edu</a>)\r\nProfessor Emeritus\r\nAGNR-Plant Sciences and Landscape Architecture\r\nUniversity of Maryland\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Dr. Sangeeta Ray</strong> (<a href="mailto:rays@umd.edu">rays@umd.edu</a>)\r\nProfessor &amp; Director\r\nAHRU-English\r\nUniversity of Maryland\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Dr. Jon T. Sumida</strong> (<a href="mailto:jtsumida@umd.edu">jtsumida@umd.edu</a>)\r\nAssociate Professor\r\nAHRU-History\r\nUniversity of Maryland\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Dr. Seung-Kyung Kim</strong> (<a href="mailto:skim2@umd.edu">skim2@umd.edu</a>)\r\nAssociate Professor\r\nAHRU-Women''s Studies\r\nUniversity of Maryland\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Dr. James Gimpel</strong> (<a href="mailto:jgimpel@umd.edu">jgimpel@umd.edu</a>)\r\nProfessor\r\nBSOS-Government &amp; Politics\r\nUniversity of Maryland\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Dr. Sonalde Desai</strong> (<a href="mailto:sdesai@umd.edu">sdesai@umd.edu</a>)\r\nProfessor\r\nBSOS-Sociology\r\nUniversity of Maryland\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Dr. Marylu McEwen</strong> (<a href="mailto:mmcewen@umd.edu">mmcewen@umd.edu</a>)\r\nAssociate Professor Emerita\r\nEDUC-Counseling and Personnel Services\r\nUniversity of Maryland\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Dr. Sunmin Lee</strong> (<a href="mailto:sunmin@umd.edu">sunmin@umd.edu</a>)\r\nAssociate Professor\r\nSPHL-Epidemiology &amp; Biostatistics\r\nUniversity of Maryland\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<img src="http://localhost/%7Erajankz/aast/media/images/people/iwamoto.jpg" alt="" width="97px" height="113px" /><strong>Dr. Derek Iwamoto</strong>(<a href="mailto:diwamoto@umd.edu">diwamoto@umd.edu</a>)\r\nResearch Assistant Professor\r\nDepartment of Psychology\r\nUniversity of Maryland\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nDr. Iwamoto’s research addresses health disparities experienced by traditionally underserved and understudied groups such as Asian Americans by first identifying socio-cultural factors and mechanisms that influence the development in binge drinking and alcohol-related problems, and second, by conducting translational research to inform and augment substance abuse treatment and interventions targeting at-risk ethnic and racial minority adolescents and young adults.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTo date, his work has contributed to the literature by examining the influence of socio-cultural factors such racial socialization (i.e., racial consciousness, racial/ethnic group attachment) and gender socialization or the beliefs, attitudes and expectations of what it means to be a man or woman, on alcohol/substance abuse and mental health problems among ethnically diverse populations. Dr. Iwamoto recently edited the first ever book on counseling interventions with Asian American men:\r\n<em>Liu, W. M., Iwamoto, D. K., &amp; Chae, M. (Eds.) (2010). Culturally Responsive Counseling Interventions with Asian American Men. Routledge Press.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nUndergraduates or graduate students interested in conducting research with Dr. Iwamoto should contact him directly.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Faculty & Staff', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'faculty-staff', '', '', '2012-06-29 04:34:20', '2012-06-29 04:34:20', '', 18, 'http://localhost/~rajankz/newaast/?page_id=117', 2, 'page', '', 0),
