(119, 1, '2012-06-29 04:35:28', '2012-06-29 04:35:28', 'The Asian American Studies Program (AAST) was formed from a joint effort between undergraduate students and faculty. In 1991, the University of Maryland offered its first course in Asian Americans Studies. In response to a series of student and faculty efforts from 1995-1996 and in recognition of the benefit to the broader community, the university officially launched the Asian American Studies Program in January 2000 by appointing a part-time director, part-time instructors and student staff.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIn the winter of 2001, the university hired two full-time faculty members to serve as the core of the program, enabling the expansion of courses and research, as well as the the successful passage of an Asian American Studies certificate program. In the summer of 2006, the university hired its first permanent director, <strong>Dr. Larry Hajime Shinagawa</strong>, and approved the minor in Asian American Studies soon after.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nToday, there are more than 20 faculty members at the University of Maryland associated with the Asian American Studies Program, and an average of 500 students enroll in our courses each semester. In the past, AAST collaborated with the Smithsonian Institution on the APA Program at the 2010 Smithsonian Folklife Festival. We currently work closely with APA community organizations and have strong research ties with the Census Bureau, as well as other agencies.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2>Asian American Studies Program Timeline</h2>\r\n<h3>2009</h3>\r\nThe Asian American Studies Program compiled the <em>2009-2011 National Directory of Scholarships, Internships, and Fellowships for Asian American and Pacific Islander Students</em> in partnership with the Organization of Chinese Americans (OCA), the Japanese American Citizens League (JACL), and State Farm. AAST also began work on<em>A Portrait of Japanese Americans</em>, a report on demographics, and on the 2010 Smithsonian Folklife Festival.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h3>2008</h3>\r\nThe United States Department of Education designated the Asian American Studies Program an Asian American Native American Pacific Islander Serving-Institution (AANAPISI), awarding a grant of $2.4 million to contribute towards expanding the program and building sustainability. Working with OCA, AAST also released its first demographic research report on ethnic groups within Asian America,<em> A Portrait of Chinese Americans</em>.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h3>2007</h3>\r\nThe University Senate approved the Asian American Studies minor program proposal, allowing students to enroll as minors in the Fall 2007 semester. AAST also hosted its first Annual Graduation Ceremony, recognizing four students for receiving their AAST academic certificates. AAST co-sponsored a forum on Asian American perspectives following the Virginia Tech tragedy that was covered by National Public Radio, C-SPAN, CBS, Asian Fortune, and other major media outlets. AAST also appointed its first permanent program coordinator, Ms. Lynne Chiao.', 'Program History', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'program-history', '', '', '2012-06-29 04:35:28', '2012-06-29 04:35:28', '', 18, 'http://localhost/~rajankz/newaast/?page_id=119', 3, 'page', '', 0),
